n of the Iberian surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."]},{"name":"Mandes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Pedro, Armando, Joaquin, Jose Inez, Tomasa.","Altered form of Portuguese   Mendes  ."]},{"name":"Mendy","meanings":["West African (Guinea Bissau, Senegal, and the Gambia): name found among the Manjak people, thought to be a shortened and altered form of Portuguese   Mendes  .","English (Buckinghamshire): variant of <b>Menday</b>, itself a variant of   Mundy  ."]},{"name":"Menendez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Luis, Juan, Ramon, Angel, Jorge, Fernando, Francisco, Rafael, Mario.  Portuguese Marcio.","Spanish (<b>Menéndez</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Men(d)endo</i>, a hypercorrected form of the Visigothic personal name <i>Hermenegild</i>, composed of the elements <i>ermen</i>, <i>irmen</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gild</i> ‘tribute’. This personal name was borne by a 6th-century member of the Visigothic royal house, who was converted from Arianism to the Catholic faith and became an enormously popular saint, as a result of which the personal name was very common in Spain in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"Gonçalo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Visigothic: from a personal name formed with <i>gund</i> ‘battle, strife’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gonçalo Mendes Chançarel was born about 1210, in Portugal, his father, Mendo Afonso de Brito, was 32 and his mother, Miana Elvira Afonso, was 34. He married Marinha Martins Barregão about 1230, in Portugal. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1210–":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1210–1300":"1210–1300","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1220–1284":"1